title: For Sale:  Walther P88
postcontent:
The Walther P88 was developed by Carl Walther in Waffenfabrik Germany in 1988. During its production it was designed for the world police market, law enforcement, and military use with a high capacity, double stacked magazine. 
The Walther P88 was discontinued in 1996 and replaced by the slightly smaller and lighter P88 Compact, which was even cheaper to manufacture. THIS IS THE ORIGINAL 102MM BARREL MODEL (NOT THE LESS ACCURATE AND "CHEAPER" COMPACT VERSION).

The P88 is highly regarded among sport shooters and collectors do to its exceptional accuracy (1.5 to 2 inch groups at 25 years) and high quality construction. 

The P 88 is insensitive to variations in ammunition, and it is the only Walther made that is completely ambidextrous. Its double action and integral safeties combined with a high capacity magazine make it superior to everything previously made.

This Walther P88 is in excellent condition and has been rated at 98%. It is in the original box, wrapped in the original plastic bag, with two magazines, cleaning rod, original test target, owners manual, and safety manual.  

Don't let this rare and beautiful gun pass you by, as that this one of a kind would certainly be a proud part of your collection.

Asking $1350 obo

title: For Sale/Trade:  ** SOLD ** 1944 Inland Div. M1 Carbine
postcontent:
** SOLD **


I have decided to narrow down my collecting and make some changes in the direction I am going and need to make some room.

Rifle:

Up for Sale or Trade is a 1944 Inland Div M1 Carbine
Rifle is NOT an import nor is it import marked.

Rifle comes with 3 magazines, original butt stock 2 cell mag holder
original m1 carbine sling. I am not an expert on the M1 Carbine and
don't claim to be.  I have taken a lot of photo's of the carbine which can
tell more of the rifle then I can.

I would say the rifle probably has been arsenal refurbished and the serial number puts it in the Jan-August 1944' production range. I would put the bore condition in an overall fair condition, it is bright but show possibility of some frosting. I tried to take a couple of photo's of the bore, I don't have a bore scope so not able to get a real good look.

The Barrel is undated but is a WW-II barrel as it is marked " BI " front of swaged gas cylinder which indicate it is an Brown-Lipe-Chapin Division
General Motors Corporation barrel Syracuse, New York

The Stock appears to have been repaired in a couple of places, I do not
know who did the repairs. I have taken pictures of this area as well.
The rifle shoots fine and stock gives no problem. It is properly marked with
the Cartouche on the stock as well.

I completed a M1 Carbine Data sheet on the breakdown of this carbine and I have included it also in the pictures.  I do not know that the TE or ME would be as I dont have gauges for it.  Carbine does pass a quick bullet test, picture taken of this as well

Best I can say is check out the photos for much better ideal of the carbine.

Sale Price:  $550 if needing to be shipped includes shipping
                   $525 if bought local-FTF

title: For Sale/Trade:  Saiga .223/5.56

The civilian import model of the AK-102, this Saiga rifle comes from the same factory as its military counterpart.  Even though labeled as .223, the robust Russian military engineering lets this rifle eat the much more common 5.56 NATO round with ease.  Like any AK variant, this rifle can run wet, dirty, or even partially damaged, though it's in perfect condition at the moment.  With a good shooter, and decent ammo, accuracy can be expected to hover around 2-3 MOA, a significant improvement over almost any AK.

This is the standard sporter import model, so there is no 922r concern with parts count.  I purchased it as a project rifle, but simply couldn't find the time to toy with all the neat little parts I could find for it.

I will sell the rifle for $400, or trade for a bolt action rifle of similar value (Marin X7, Savage 11, etc.).

title: Want To Buy:  Denver Shooting Club, Thoughts?
location: Denver Metro and suburbs, Denver, Colorado
postcontent:
**Please take time to read through and leave helpful feedback**

Anyone hunter, target shooter or gun enthusiast who has lived in Denver knows that the capital city of one of the most gun/hunter friendly states provides few opportunities to maintain proficiency as a hunter or marksman. While there is a selection of shooting ranges in the city, albeit dwindling, many are considered to be over-priced, un-welcoming, or unsuitable for certain types of shooting (3-gun, quick draw, long range, etc.). The easiest alternative is to find private land with owners consent. However, few city-dwellers have easy contact with farmers and ranchers, and few farmers and ranchers are overly eager to have gun-toting city dwellers traipse about their land. That leaves public land, owned by the Departments of Wildlife, the Forestry Department, or the Bureau of Land Management (BLM). One look at a government map of the state of Colorado shows an abundant supply of free-to-shoot land... on the western slope. Us Front-Rangers are mainly limited to Pawnee National Grasslands in the northeast, and Comanche in the south. I have personally been to both Pawnee and Comanche, and can testify that while they are both no-frills nothing-fancy areas to shoot, they are perfect for any activity you can think of, within the confines of the law, obviously. The only draw-back to Pawnee for Denver shooters is the drive. From Exit 1-25 exit 200, the shooting area I have visited was just around 90 miles away, and that was the well known "busy" area. There are more remote areas with longer distances to backdrops for distance shooters, but those may be another 20 miles away. For a solo outing to blow off some rounds or to dial in a rifle, a 160-200 mile round trip drive is less than ideal. Which made me ask; has anyone seen, heard of, or thought about a Denver Metro Shooting Club? I am not talking about a gun club with fees or weird initiations or mandatory meetings, I am think about something more relaxed and useful.
The idea I have would be to make a Facebook page where people could simply post where they are going to shoot, when, for how long, and how many people they could take. Also, they could list what they might expect to help out with gas, as well as rules they would want to abide by. 
An example would be;

1 shooter going to Pawnee Sunday, August 26th. Departing Denver at 0930, will return home 1700. Have room for 3 more shooters. Would like $10 per passenger for fuel, or a box of 12ga or 5.56. No drinking, no littering.

I understand many are wary of strangers, but have to say everyone I have met on Armslist has been really cool so far. I've sold magazines to military veterans and purchased sights and rifles from active and retired law enforcement. I think that if we are honest about what the group could be, efficient car-pooling and friendly shooting with responsible individuals, this could be a success. It could also be a great way for hunters to network and make new hunting friends. Small-gamers could gain access to new prairie dog and rabbit land, and any friends of farmers can help their farmer friends out with a plethora of new responsible shooters. There will be no tolerance for the shooters that spend all afternoon drinking and shooting and leave hundreds of shotgun shells and dozens of beer cans littered about giving a bad name to shooters everywhere.

If something similar to what I have described already exists, I would love to know about it. Please feel free to email me at REDACTED and let me know what kind of shooting you would like to do, and maybe a short paragraph including your shooting experience. If there is a strong enough response, I will take the next step in making this real.

Thanks so much for taking the time to read this. I would appreciate any feedback you may have.

-Mark
